04667nam a22006135i 9780226816432DE-B159720220424125308.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220424t20222022ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a2021035773  a9780226816432  a(DE-B1597)590679  a(OCoLC)1289373104  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL00aE185.89.I56bT47 2022 4aE185.89.I56bT47 2022 7aLIT0000002bisacsh04a973/.04960732231 aThompson, Mark Christian, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aPhenomenal Blackness :bBlack Power, Philosophy, and Theory /cMark Christian Thompson. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2022] 4c©2022  a1 online resource (208 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aThinking Literature00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction. The Essence of the Matter -- t1 The Politics of Black Friendship: Gadamer, Baldwin, and the Black Hermeneutic -- t2 The Aardvark of History: Malcom X, Language, and Power -- t3 Black Aesthetic Autonomy: Ralph Ellison, Amiri Baraka, and “Literary Negro- ness” -- t4 The Revolutionary Will Not Be Hypnotized: Eldridge Cleaver and Black Ideology -- t5 Unrepeatable: Angela Y. Davis and Black Critical Theory -- tConclusion. Black Aesthetic Theory -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis unorthodox account of 1960s Black thought rigorously details the field’s debts to German critical theory and explores a forgotten tradition of Black singularity. Phenomenal Blackness examines the changing interdisciplinary investments of key mid-century Black writers and thinkers, including the growing interest in German philosophy and critical theory. Mark Christian Thompson analyzes this shift in intellectual focus across the post-war decades, placing Black Power thought in a philosophical context. Prior to the 1960s, sociologically oriented thinkers such as W. E. B. Du Bois had understood Blackness as a singular set of socio-historical characteristics. In contrast, writers such as Amiri Baraka, James Baldwin, Angela Y. Davis, Eldridge Cleaver, and Malcolm X were drawn to notions of an African essence, an ontology of Black being. With these perspectives, literary language came to be seen as the primary social expression of Blackness. For this new way of thinking, the works of philosophers such as Adorno, Habermas, and Marcuse were a vital resource, allowing for continued cultural-materialist analysis while accommodating the hermeneutical aspects of Black religious thought. Thompson argues that these efforts to reimagine Black singularity led to a phenomenological understanding of Blackness—a “Black aesthetic dimension” wherein aspirational models for Black liberation might emerge.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aAfrican American aesthetics. 0aAfrican American philosophy. 0aAfrican AmericansxIntellectual lifey20th century. 0aAmerican literaturexAfrican American authorsxGerman influences. 0aCritical theoryxHistory. 0aCriticismzUnited StatesxHistory. 0aPhilosophy, German. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh  ahermeneutics, critical theory, Black Power, African American philosophy, African American theory, Blackness, aesthetics, German philosophy, civil rights, 1960s.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311073919008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311076650940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226816432423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226816432/original  a978-3-11-073919-0  University of Chicago Complete eBook-Package 2021b2021  a978-3-11-076650-9  University of Chica